---
import BaseLayout from "~/layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About OpenCDD — the name, the logo, the spirit"
  description="OpenCDD's name, logo, and design philosophy. The I Ching hexagram Dui (Lake), the principle of 求同存異, and why a zen palette fits a common data dictionary."
>
  <article class="mx-auto max-w-3xl space-y-16">
    {/* ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
        INTRO
       ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── */}
    <header class="space-y-5 border-b border-paper-300 pb-12">
      <p class="text-[11px] font-medium uppercase tracking-[0.15em] text-hex-700">
        About OpenCDD
      </p>
      <h1 class="font-display text-4xl leading-tight tracking-tight text-ink-900 sm:text-5xl">
        One vocabulary. Many domains. The same identifier everywhere it appears.
      </h1>
      <p class="text-base leading-relaxed text-ink-600">
        OpenCDD is an open-source ecosystem of tools around the IEC Common
        Data Dictionary. The dictionary itself is maintained by IEC TC 3;
        we build the browser, the Ruby model, and the TypeScript port.
        This page is about the name, the logo, and the design choices.
      </p>
    </header>

    {/* ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
        THE NAME — 求同存異
       ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── */}
    <section class="space-y-5">
      <p class="text-[10px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.15em] text-ink-500">
        § 1 — The name
      </p>
      <h2 class="font-display text-3xl tracking-tight text-ink-900">求同存異</h2>
      <div class="space-y-4 text-[15px] leading-relaxed text-ink-700">
        <p>
          The Chinese phrase <span class="font-display text-ink-900">求同存異</span> —
          <em>qiú tóng cún yì</em> — translates literally as
          <em>seek the common, preserve the differences</em>. It is a
          diplomatic and philosophical principle: find the shared ground
          without erasing what makes each party distinct.
        </p>
        <p>
          This is exactly what the IEC Common Data Dictionary does.
          Manufacturers, regulators, suppliers, and engineers across
          electrotechnology, industrial measurement, low-voltage
          switchgear, and household equipment each maintain their own
          terminology. CDD does not ask them to give it up. Instead, it
          binds every entity — every class, property, value list, value
          term, unit, and relation — to a globally unique
          <strong>International Registration Data Identifier (IRDI)</strong>.
          The vocabulary is shared. The terminology is preserved.
        </p>
        <p>
          That is the structural foundation for everything OpenCDD cares
          about: encapsulation (private dictionaries that interoperate
          with public ones), reuse (one property definition cited
          everywhere it appears), the four-layer ontology
          (meta-class → class → instance → powertype), interoperability,
          and extensibility. <strong>Common ground, preserved
          differences.</strong>
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    {/* ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
        THE LOGO
       ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── */}
    <section class="space-y-6">
      <p class="text-[10px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.15em] text-ink-500">
        § 2 — The logo
      </p>
      <h2 class="font-display text-3xl tracking-tight text-ink-900">
        The hexagram <span class="text-hex-700">☱</span> Dui · 兌 · Lake
      </h2>

      <div class="grid gap-6 sm:grid-cols-[1fr_2fr]">
        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-paper-300 bg-paper-50 p-6 text-center">
          <img
            src="/img/logo-512.jpg"
            alt="OpenCDD logo: an isometric hexagonal prism holding three interconnected water-blue data pools, capped by the I Ching hexagram Dui (Lake) in golden orange."
            width="256"
            height="256"
            loading="lazy"
            class="mx-auto h-48 w-48 rounded-lg object-cover shadow-sm"
          />
          <p class="mt-3 text-[11px] uppercase tracking-wide text-ink-500">
            OpenCDD · 2026
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="space-y-4 text-[15px] leading-relaxed text-ink-700">
          <p>
            The logo is built around the I Ching hexagram{" "}
            <span class="font-display text-2xl text-hex-700">☱</span>{" "}
            (<strong>Dui</strong>, 兌) — the hexagram for <em>Lake</em>.
            Dui is drawn as three horizontal lines with the top line
            broken in the middle. In the I Ching it carries the imagery
            of <em>joyous exchange</em>: a lake collects water from many
            streams and holds it as one body, while remaining open to
            the sky.
          </p>
          <p>
            We chose Dui because it is the perfect metaphor for a common
            data dictionary:
          </p>
          <ul class="space-y-1.5">
            <li>
              <strong>Many streams, one lake.</strong> Domains, languages,
              and manufacturers each contribute their own properties; the
              dictionary collects them into one body of identifiers.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Interconnected pools.</strong> The water-blue pools
              inside the prism are not isolated — they touch and flow into
              each other, the way properties reference classes and
              classes inherit from one another.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>The capstone is the hexagram.</strong> On top of
              the prism sits ☱, golden and quiet — the principle that
              holds the rest together.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Open to the sky.</strong> The off-white background,
              the ripples, the absence of a frame: the system is open,
              extendable, never closed off.
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="rounded-xl border-l-4 border-hex-400 bg-paper-100 p-4 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-700">
        <strong class="text-hex-700">Why a hexagram, not a star or a graph?</strong>
        CDD is older than the modern web and deeper than a graph: it is a
        four-layer ontology with native power-type semantics. The I Ching
        hexagrams are the oldest continuously used formal modelling system
        in the world. Using one to mark the other is a small acknowledgement
        that the problems CDD solves — naming, classifying, relating — are
        not new.
      </div>
    </section>

    {/* ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
        THE COLOURS
       ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── */}
    <section class="space-y-5">
      <p class="text-[10px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.15em] text-ink-500">
        § 3 — The colours
      </p>
      <h2 class="font-display text-3xl tracking-tight text-ink-900">
        Wabi-sabi, water, and a single capstone.
      </h2>
      <p class="text-[15px] leading-relaxed text-ink-700">
        The palette is borrowed from the logo: muted earth tones, soft
        water blues, sage greens, and a single golden accent. It is
        deliberately quiet. CDD is a reference work; the typography and
        the data should carry the page, not the chrome.
      </p>

      <div class="grid grid-cols-2 gap-3 sm:grid-cols-3 lg:grid-cols-6">
        <div class="rounded-lg border border-paper-300 overflow-hidden">
          <div class="h-16" style="background:#1a1814"></div>
          <div class="p-2">
            <p class="font-mono text-[10px] text-ink-700">#1A1814</p>
            <p class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-wide text-ink-500">Ink</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-lg border border-paper-300 overflow-hidden">
          <div class="h-16" style="background:#faf7f0"></div>
          <div class="p-2">
            <p class="font-mono text-[10px] text-ink-700">#FAF7F0</p>
            <p class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-wide text-ink-500">Paper</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-lg border border-paper-300 overflow-hidden">
          <div class="h-16" style="background:#e8d5b7"></div>
          <div class="p-2">
            <p class="font-mono text-[10px] text-ink-700">#E8D5B7</p>
            <p class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-wide text-ink-500">Clay</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-lg border border-paper-300 overflow-hidden">
          <div class="h-16" style="background:#8fbc8f"></div>
          <div class="p-2">
            <p class="font-mono text-[10px] text-ink-700">#8FBC8F</p>
            <p class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-wide text-ink-500">Sage</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-lg border border-paper-300 overflow-hidden">
          <div class="h-16" style="background:#7fb3d5"></div>
          <div class="p-2">
            <p class="font-mono text-[10px] text-ink-700">#7FB3D5</p>
            <p class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-wide text-ink-500">Water</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-lg border border-paper-300 overflow-hidden">
          <div class="h-16" style="background:#f4a460"></div>
          <div class="p-2">
            <p class="font-mono text-[10px] text-ink-700">#F4A460</p>
            <p class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-wide text-ink-500">Hexagram</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <ul class="space-y-2 text-[14px] leading-relaxed text-ink-700">
        <li>
          <strong class="text-ink-900">Paper</strong> is the background — warm off-white,
          like unbleached washi. Calmer than pure white.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong class="text-ink-900">Ink</strong> is the text — warm charcoal, slightly
          browner than zinc, never pure black.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong class="text-ink-900">Clay</strong> is the surface tone of the prism — the
          primary brand beige, used in cards and dividers.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong class="text-ink-900">Sage</strong> marks the natural ground — moss and
          grass around the prism. Used for secondary surfaces and
          success states.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong class="text-ink-900">Water</strong> is the data accent — soft blue for
          links, IRDIs, and highlights. The colour of the pools.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong class="text-ink-900">Hexagram gold</strong> is the single loud accent —
          the capstone colour, used sparingly for primary CTAs and brand
          moments. Never for body text.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    {/* ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
        THE SPIRIT
       ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── */}
    <section class="space-y-5">
      <p class="text-[10px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.15em] text-ink-500">
        § 4 — The spirit
      </p>
      <h2 class="font-display text-3xl tracking-tight text-ink-900">
        Four layers, two directions, one identifier.
      </h2>
      <div class="space-y-4 text-[15px] leading-relaxed text-ink-700">
        <p>
          CDD is structurally unusual. It is not a class diagram and it
          is not an RDF graph. It is a four-layer ontology:
        </p>
        <ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-1 pl-3">
          <li>the dictionary schema (defined normatively in EXPRESS);</li>
          <li>the meta-classes (Class, Property, ValueList, ValueTerm, Unit, Relation);</li>
          <li>the dictionary content (the actual classes and properties);</li>
          <li>the instances — which, when <code class="font-mono text-xs">class_type</code> allows, can themselves act as classes elsewhere.</li>
        </ol>
        <p>
          That last step — instances-as-classes, the power-type pattern —
          is what makes CDD <em>extensible</em>. A new domain can extend
          an existing class without modifying it; a private dictionary
          can interoperate with the public one without losing its own
          identity. The mechanism is the spec's
          <code class="font-mono text-xs">class_type</code> attribute
          (<code class="font-mono text-xs">CATEGORICAL CLASS</code>,
          <code class="font-mono text-xs">FEATURE CLASS</code>) and the
          <code class="font-mono text-xs">is_case_of</code> relationship.
          See <a href="/docs/cdd-ontology-vs-uml-rdf/" class="text-hex-700 underline underline-offset-2">CDD ontology vs UML and RDF</a>
          for the full argument.
        </p>
        <p>
          Two directions of reuse, one identifier scheme. That is the
          whole point. OpenCDD exists to make that point legible,
          browseable, and machine-usable.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    {/* ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
        THE ECOSYSTEM
       ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── */}
    <section class="space-y-5">
      <p class="text-[10px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.15em] text-ink-500">
        § 5 — The ecosystem
      </p>
      <h2 class="font-display text-3xl tracking-tight text-ink-900">
        Where OpenCDD lives.
      </h2>
      <div class="overflow-hidden rounded-xl border border-paper-300">
        <table class="min-w-full text-sm">
          <thead class="bg-paper-100 text-[11px] uppercase tracking-wide text-ink-500">
            <tr>
              <th class="px-4 py-2 text-left">Repository</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-2 text-left">Role</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="divide-y divide-paper-200">
            <tr>
              <td class="px-4 py-2 font-mono text-xs">
                <a href="https://github.com/opencdd/opencdd-ruby" class="text-hex-700 underline underline-offset-2">opencdd/opencdd-ruby</a>
              </td>
              <td class="px-4 py-2 text-ink-700">
                The Ruby model — the canonical implementation. Reads
                <code class="font-mono text-xs">.xls</code> and
                <code class="font-mono text-xs">.xlsx</code>, exports JSON and CDDAL.
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="px-4 py-2 font-mono text-xs">
                <a href="https://github.com/opencdd/opencdd-ts" class="text-hex-700 underline underline-offset-2">opencdd/opencdd-ts</a>
              </td>
              <td class="px-4 py-2 text-ink-700">
                <code class="font-mono text-xs">@opencdd/models</code> on npm —
                the TypeScript port of the model types.
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="px-4 py-2 font-mono text-xs">
                <a href="https://github.com/opencdd/opencdd.github.io" class="text-hex-700 underline underline-offset-2">opencdd/opencdd.github.io</a>
              </td>
              <td class="px-4 py-2 text-ink-700">
                This browser — Astro + Vue + Tailwind. Pre-renders every
                entity page; searched with Pagefind.
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="px-4 py-2 font-mono text-xs text-ink-500">opencdd/editor</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-2 text-ink-500">
                <em>Planned.</em> A browser-based editor for authoring
                CDD content.
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="px-4 py-2 font-mono text-xs text-ink-500">opencdd/cdd-data</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-2 text-ink-500">
                <em>Private.</em> The data pipeline: scrapers, source
                <code class="font-mono text-xs">.xls</code>, release workflow.
              </td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </section>

    {/* ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
        RELATIONSHIP TO IEC
       ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── */}
    <section class="space-y-4 rounded-2xl border border-paper-300 bg-paper-100 p-6">
      <p class="text-[10px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.15em] text-ink-500">
        A note on IEC
      </p>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-700">
        OpenCDD is <strong>not</strong> affiliated with the International
        Electrotechnical Commission. IEC owns the standards (IEC 61360
        and friends) and the dictionary content; we own the tooling. The
        logo's hexagram ☱ and the philosophy of 求同存異 are our framing,
        not IEC's. For the canonical publications, see the
        <a href="https://webstore.iec.ch/" class="text-hex-700 underline underline-offset-2">IEC webstore</a>.
      </p>
    </section>

    <footer class="border-t border-paper-300 pt-8 text-sm text-ink-500">
      <p>
        OpenCDD is open source. The browser lives at
        <a href="https://github.com/opencdd/opencdd.github.io" class="text-hex-700 underline underline-offset-2">opencdd/opencdd.github.io</a>;
        contributions are welcome. See
        <a href="/docs/contributing/" class="text-hex-700 underline underline-offset-2">the contributing guide</a>
        for how to add docs, fix the UI, or improve the data pipeline.
      </p>
    </footer>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
